item.description:
【<p><em>Chris Watts is Head of Enterprise Engineering at OpenRouter, building infrastructure for AI applications. Previously at Amazon and a startup founder.</em></p><p>As large language models become core infrastructure for more and more applications, teams are discovering a familiar challenge in a new context: you can't improve what you can't see. Whether you're routing requests across multiple AI providers, managing costs across dozens of models, or debugging why a particular prompt is timing out in production, observability is no longer optional for LLM-powered systems.</p><p>At <u><a href="https://openrouter.ai">OpenRouter</a></u>, we provide a unified API that gives developers access to hundreds of models from providers like OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, and Meta through a single integration. We handle load balancing, provider fallbacks, and model routing so teams can focus on building their applications rather than managing multiple API keys and billing accounts.</p><p>But access to models is only half the story. When you're running AI workloads in production, you need to understand how those workloads are performing, what they're costing, and where they're failing. That's why we built <u><a href="https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/features/broadcast">Broadcast</a></u>, a feature that automatically sends traces from your OpenRouter requests to observability platforms like  <u><a href="https://grafana.com/products/cloud/">Grafana Cloud</a></u>, with no additional instrumentation required in your application code.</p><p>In this post, we'll walk through how Broadcast works with Grafana Cloud, and share some of the real-world use cases we're seeing.</p><h2>Why LLM observability is different</h2><p>Traditional application monitoring focuses on familiar signals: HTTP status codes, response times, and error rates. LLM applications use those same signals, but they also introduce entirely new dimensions that teams need to track:</p><ul><li><strong>Token usage and costs</strong>: Every request consumes tokens, and costs vary across models. A single prompt sent to GPT-4o vs. Claude 3.5 Haiku can differ dramatically.</li><li><strong>Model behavior variability</strong>: The same prompt can produce different results depending on which model or provider handles it. When you're using fallbacks or load balancing across providers, understanding which model actually served a request matters.</li><li><strong>Latency profiles</strong>: LLM latency isn't just about total response time. Time to first token, tokens per second, and total generation time each tell a different part of the story.</li><li><strong>Non-deterministic failures</strong>: LLM requests can fail in subtle ways, like hitting rate limits, receiving truncated outputs, or producing responses that technically succeed but don't meet quality expectations.</li></ul><p>Most teams start by adding logging and metrics to their own application code, but this approach quickly becomes difficult to maintain, especially when you're using multiple models and providers. What you really want is observability that's built into the infrastructure layer, where the routing and model selection actually happen.</p><h2>How OpenRouter Broadcast works with Grafana Cloud</h2><p>OpenRouter Broadcast works by automatically generating <u><a href="https://opentelemetry.io/">OpenTelemetry</a></u> traces for every API request and sending them to your configured destinations. There's no SDK to install, no code to change, and no additional latency added to your requests. You configure it once in your OpenRouter dashboard, and every request flowing through your account is traced.</p><p>For Grafana Cloud, traces are sent via the standard OTLP HTTP/JSON endpoint directly to <u><a href="https://grafana.com/products/cloud/traces/">Grafana Cloud Traces</a></u>, the cloud-based tracing backend powered by <u><a href="https://grafana.com/oss/tempo/">Tempo</a></u> OSS. Each trace includes rich attributes following OpenTelemetry semantic conventions for generative AI:</p><ul><li><strong>Model information</strong>: Which model was requested, which model actually served the response, and which provider handled it</li><li><strong>Token usage</strong>: Input tokens, output tokens, and total tokens consumed</li><li><strong>Timing data</strong>: Total request duration, time to first token, and generation speed</li><li><strong>Cost data</strong>: The cost in USD for each request</li><li><strong>Status and errors</strong>: Whether the request succeeded, why generation ended, and any error details</li><li><strong>Custom metadata</strong>: Any application-specific context you attach to your requests, like user IDs, session IDs, or feature flags</li></ul><p>Once traces are flowing into Grafana Cloud, you can query them using <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/tempo/latest/traceql/">TraceQL</a></u>, build dashboards, and set up alerts, all using the same Grafana Cloud interface your team already knows.</p><p>You can see span rate, error rates, and duration for OpenRouter traces at a glance:</p><p>You can drill into into a single LLM Generation trace to inspect timing and service details:</p><p>Full span attributes show the prompt, model, token count, and completion, all captured via OpenTelemetry:</p><h2>Real-world use cases</h2><p>Here are some of the ways teams are using OpenRouter Broadcast with Grafana Cloud today.</p><h3>Tracking costs across models and features</h3><p>One of the most immediate use cases is cost visibility. When you're routing requests across multiple models, it's easy to lose track of where your spend is going. With traces flowing into Grafana Cloud, teams build dashboards that break down costs by model, API key, user, or any custom metadata they attach to their requests.</p><p>For example, a team running both a customer-facing chatbot and an internal document processing pipeline can use separate API keys or custom metadata to attribute costs to each workload. A simple TraceQL query like this surfaces all requests from a specific environment:</p><pre><code>{ resource.service.name = "openrouter" && span.trace.metadata.environment = "production" }</code></pre><p>This kind of visibility lets engineering leads and finance teams answer questions like "How much did our AI features cost last week?" or "Which model is giving us the best cost-per-quality ratio?" without building custom analytics infrastructure.</p><h3>Monitoring latency and performance</h3><p>LLM latency directly impacts user experience. A chatbot that takes 8 seconds to start responding feels broken, even if the final output is excellent. With OpenRouter traces in Grafana Cloud, teams can monitor latency trends over time, set alerts for slow requests, and compare performance across models.</p><p>TraceQL makes it easy to find outliers:</p><p></p><pre><code>{ resource.service.name = "openrouter" && duration > 5s }</code></pre><p>Teams often build Grafana dashboards that show p50, p95, and p99 latency by model, which helps them make informed decisions about which models to use for latency-sensitive vs. batch workloads.</p><h3>Debugging errors and failed requests</h3><p>When something goes wrong in an LLM pipeline, the cause isn't always obvious. Was it a rate limit? A poorly created prompt? A provider outage? With distributed traces in Grafana Cloud, teams can quickly filter for errors and drill into individual requests to see exactly what happened:</p><p></p><pre><code>{ resource.service.name = "openrouter" && status = error }</code></pre><p>Each trace includes the model, provider, error details, and timing information, giving teams the context they need to diagnose issues without digging through application logs.</p><h3>Usage analytics and capacity planning</h3><p>As AI features grow, teams need to understand usage patterns to plan capacity and negotiate contracts with providers. Grafana Cloud dashboards built on OpenRouter traces can show request volume over time, token consumption trends, and model popularity, all without any additional instrumentation.</p><p>Teams use this data to track how usage is growing and answer questions like: "Are we approaching our rate limits?" or "Should we shift more traffic to a cheaper model for this use case?" </p><h2>Getting started</h2><p>Setting up the integration takes just a few minutes:</p><p>1. <strong>Get your Grafana Cloud credentials</strong>: You'll need your OTLP gateway endpoint, instance ID, and an API token with <code>traces:write</code> permissions from your <u><a href="https://grafana.com/auth/sign-in">Grafana Cloud portal</a></u>.</p><p>2. <strong>Enable Broadcast in OpenRouter</strong>: Navigate to <u><a href="https://openrouter.ai/settings/broadcast">Settings > Observability</a></u> in your OpenRouter dashboard and toggle Broadcast on.</p><p>3. <strong>Configure Grafana Cloud as a destination</strong>: Enter your Grafana Cloud credentials and click <strong>Test Connection</strong> to verify the setup.</p><p>4.<strong> Start querying traces</strong>: Once configured, every OpenRouter request will generate a trace in Grafana Cloud. Navigate to Explore, select your Tempo data source, and run <code>{ resource.service.name = "openrouter" }</code> to see your traces.</p><p>For detailed setup instructions, including how to find your OTLP endpoint and create API tokens, check out our <u><a href="https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/features/broadcast/grafana">Broadcast to Grafana Cloud documentation</a></u>.</p><h3>Adding custom metadata</h3><p>To get the most out of the integration, we recommend attaching custom metadata to your OpenRouter requests. This metadata flows through to Grafana Cloud as span attributes, making it easy to filter and group traces by your own application context:</p><p></p><pre><code>{
"model": "openai/gpt-4o",
"messages": [{ "role": "user", "content": "Summarize this document..." }],
"user": "user_12345",
"session_id": "session_abc",
"trace": {
"trace_name": "Document Summary",
"environment": "production",
"feature": "summarization"
}
}
</code></pre><p>You can then query these attributes in TraceQL:</p><p></p><pre><code>{ resource.service.name = "openrouter" && span.trace.metadata.feature = "summarization" }</code></pre><h3>Privacy controls</h3><p>For teams working with sensitive data, Broadcast supports a <u><a href="https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/features/broadcast/overview#privacy-mode">Privacy Mode</a></u> that excludes prompt and completion content from traces while still sending all operational data like token usage, costs, timing, and model information. This lets you get full observability without exposing the content of your LLM interactions.</p><h2>What's next</h2><p>We're continuing to invest in making LLM observability as seamless as possible. We're adding new integrations regularly and are working on richer trace data, including more granular timing breakdowns and quality signals that can help you build even more comprehensive observability dashboards.</p><p>If you're building with LLMs and want visibility into how your AI workloads are performing, give the <u><a href="https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/features/broadcast/grafana">OpenRouter and Grafana Cloud integration</a></u> a try. You can get started with a <u><a href="https://grafana.com/auth/sign-up/create-user">free Grafana Cloud account</a></u> and an <u><a href="https://openrouter.ai">OpenRouter</a></u> account in minutes.</p><p><em>To learn more about OpenRouter's Broadcast feature and all supported destinations, visit the </em><u><em><a href="https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/features/broadcast">Broadcast documentation</a></em></u><em>. For questions or feedback, reach out to us at </em><u><em><a href="http://openrouter.ai">openrouter.ai</a></em></u><em>.</em></p><p></p>】<p><em>Chris Watts 是 OpenRouter 的企业工程主管，负责为 AI 应用程序构建基础设施。曾就职于亚马逊，是一家初创公司创始人。</em></p><p>随着大型语言模型成为越来越多应用程序的核心基础设施，团队在新的环境中发现了一个熟悉的挑战：你无法改进你看不到的东西。无论您是跨多个 AI 提供商路由请求、管理数十个模型的成本，还是调试特定提示在生产中超时的原因，对于 LLM 支持的系统来说，可观察性都不再是可选的。</p><p>在 <u><a href="https://openrouter.ai">OpenRouter</a></u>，我们提供了一个统一的 API，使开发人员可以通过单一集成访问来自 OpenAI、Anthropic、Google 和 Meta 等提供商的数百个模型。我们处理负载平衡、提供商回退和模型路由，以便团队可以专注于构建应用程序，而不是管理多个 API 密钥和计费帐户。</p><p>但是对模型的访问只是故事的一半。当您在生产环境中运行 AI 工作负载时，您需要了解这些工作负载的执行情况、成本以及故障所在。这就是我们构建<u><a href="https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/features/broadcast">广播</a></u>的原因，该功能可以自动将来自 OpenRouter 请求的跟踪信息发送到可观察性平台（例如 <u><a href="https://grafana.com/products/cloud/">Grafana Cloud</a></u>），而无需在应用程序代码中添加任何其他工具。</p><p>在此在这篇文章中，我们将介绍 Broadcast 如何与 Grafana Cloud 配合使用，并分享我们看到的一些实际用例。</p><h2>为什么 LLM 可观察性有所不同</h2><p>传统应用程序监控侧重于熟悉的信号：HTTP 状态代码、响应时间和错误率。 LLM 应用程序使用相同的信号，但它们还引入了团队需要跟踪的全新维度：</p><ul><li><strong>令牌使用和成本</strong>：每个请求都会消耗令牌，并且成本因模型而异。发送到 GPT-4o 的单个提示与 Claude 3.5 Haiku 可能会有很大差异。</li><li><strong>模型行为可变性</strong>：相同的提示可能会产生不同的结果，具体取决于处理它的模型或提供程序。当您在提供商之间使用后备或负载平衡时，了解哪个模型实际服务请求很重要。</li><li><strong>延迟概况</strong>：LLM 延迟不仅仅与总响应时间有关。第一个令牌的时间、每秒令牌和总生成时间各自讲述了故事的不同部分。</li><li><strong>非确定性故障</strong>：LLM 请求可能会以微妙的方式失败，例如达到速率限制、收到截断的输出或生成技术上成功但不符合质量预期的响应。</li></ul><p>大多数团队首先向自己的应用程序代码添加日志记录和指标，但这种方法很快就会变得难以维护，尤其是特别是当您使用多个模型和提供商时。您真正想要的是内置于基础设施层中的可观察性，路由和模型选择实际上发生在基础设施层中。</p><h2>OpenRouter Broadcast 如何与 Grafana Cloud 配合使用</h2><p>OpenRouter Broadcast 的工作原理是自动为每个 API 请求生成 <u><a href="https://opentelemetry.io/">OpenTelemetry</a></u> 跟踪并将其发送到您配置的目的地。无需安装 SDK，无需更改代码，也不会为您的请求添加额外的延迟。您在 OpenRouter 仪表板中配置一次，就会跟踪流经您帐户的每个请求。</p><p>对于 Grafana Cloud，跟踪信息将通过标准 OTLP HTTP/JSON 端点直接发送到 <u><a href="https://grafana.com/products/cloud/traces/">Grafana Cloud Traces</a></u>，这是由 <u><a 提供支持的基于云的跟踪后端href="https://grafana.com/oss/tempo/">节奏</a></u> OSS。每个跟踪都包含遵循生成式 AI 的 OpenTelemetry 语义约定的丰富属性：</p><ul><li><strong>模型信息</strong>：请求了哪个模型、哪个模型实际提供了响应以及哪个提供者处理了它</li><li><strong>令牌使用</strong>：输入令牌、输出令牌和消耗的总令牌</li><li><strong>计时数据</strong>：总请求持续时间、第一个令牌的时间和生成速度</li><li><strong>成本数据</strong>：每个请求的成本（以美元为单位）</li><li><strong>状态和错误</strong>：请求是否成功、生成结束的原因以及任何错误详细信息</li><li><strong>自定义元数据</strong>：附加到请求的任何特定于应用程序的上下文，例如用户 ID、会话 ID 或功能标志</li></ul><p>跟踪流入 Grafana Cloud 后，您可以查询它们使用 <u><a href="https://grafana.com/docs/tempo/latest/traceql/">TraceQL</a></u>、构建仪表板并设置警报，所有这些都使用您的团队已经了解的同一 Grafana Cloud 界面。</p><p>您可以一目了然地查看 OpenRouter 跟踪的跨度率、错误率和持续时间：</p><p>您可以深入了解单个 LLM Generation 跟踪以检查计时和服务详细信息：</p><p>全范围属性显示提示、模型、令牌计数和完成情况，全部通过 OpenTelemetry 捕获：</p><h2>真实用例</h2><p>以下是团队目前将 OpenRouter Broadcast 与 Grafana Cloud 结合使用的一些方法。</p><h3>跨模型和功能跟踪成本</h3><p>最直接的用例之一是成本可见性。当您跨多个模型路由请求时，很容易忘记您的支出去向。随着跟踪流入 Grafana Cloud，团队构建仪表板，按模型、API 密钥、用户或附加到请求的任何自定义元数据来细分成本。</p><p>例如，运行面向客户的聊天机器人和内部文档处理管道的团队可以使用单独的 API 密钥或自定义元数据将成本归因于每个工作负载。一个简单的特拉像这样的 ceQL 查询会显示来自特定环境的所有请求：</p><pre><code>{ resources.service.name = "openrouter" && span.trace.metadata.environment = "product" }</code></pre><p>这种可见性让工程主管和财务团队可以回答诸如“上周我们的 AI 功能花费了多少钱？”之类的问题。或“哪种模型为我们提供了最佳的性价比？”无需构建自定义分析基础设施。</p><h3>监控延迟和性能</h3><p>LLM 延迟直接影响用户体验。即使最终输出非常出色，需要 8 秒才能开始响应的聊天机器人也会让人感觉很糟糕。借助 Grafana Cloud 中的 OpenRouter 跟踪，团队可以监控一段时间内的延迟趋势，为缓慢请求设置警报，并比较不同模型的性能。</p><p>TraceQL 可以轻松查找异常值：</p><p></p><pre><code>{ resource.service.name = "openrouter" &&uration > 5s }</code></pre><p>团队经常构建显示 p50、p95、以及按模型划分的 p99 延迟，这有助于他们就使用哪些模型来处理延迟敏感型工作负载和批处理工作负载做出明智的决策。</p><h3>调试错误和失败的请求</h3><p>当 LLM 管道中出现问题时，原因并不总是显而易见的。这是速率限制吗？提示创建得不好？提供商中断？借助 Grafana Cloud 中的分布式跟踪，团队可以快速筛选错误并深入了解各个请求，以准确了解发生的情况：</p><p></p><pre><code>{ resource.service.name = "openrouter" && status = error }</code></pre><p>每个跟踪都包含模型、提供程序、错误详细信息和计时信息，为团队提供诊断问题所需的上下文，而无需深入研究应用程序日志。</p><h3>使用情况分析和容量规划</h3><p>随着人工智能功能的发展，团队需要了解使用模式来规划容量并与提供商协商合同。基于 OpenRouter 跟踪构建的 Grafana Cloud 仪表板可以显示随时间变化的请求量、令牌消耗趋势和模型流行度，所有这些都无需任何额外的工具。</p><p>团队使用这些数据来跟踪使用量的增长情况并回答诸如“我们是否接近速率限制？”之类的问题。或“针对此用例，我们是否应该将更多流量转移到更便宜的型号？” </p><h2>开始使用</h2><p>设置集成只需几分钟：</p><p>1. <strong>获取 Grafana Cloud 凭据</strong>：您需要 OTLP 网关端点、实例 ID 以及来自 <u><a href="https://grafana.com/auth/sign-in">Grafana Cloud 门户</a></u>的具有 <code>traces:write</code> 权限的 API 令牌。</p><p>2. <strong>在 OpenRouter 中启用广播</strong>：导航至 OpenRouter 仪表板中的<u><a href="https://openrouter.ai/settings/broadcast">设置 > 可观察性</a></u>，然后打开广播。</p><p>3. <strong>将 Grafana Cloud 配置为目标</strong>：输入您的 Grafana Cloud 凭据，然后单击<strong>测试连接</strong>以验证设置。</p><p>4.<strong>开始查询跟踪</strong>：配置完成后，每个 OpenRouter 请求都会在 Grafana Cloud 中生成跟踪。导航到“探索”，选择您的 Tempo 数据源，然后运行 <code>{ resource.service.name = "openrouter" }</code> 以查看您的跟踪记录。</p><p>有关详细设置说明，包括如何查找 OTLP 端点和创建 API 令牌，请查看我们的<u><a href="https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/features/broadcast/grafana">广播到 Grafana Cloud文档</a></u>。</p><h3>添加自定义元数据</h3><p>为了充分利用集成，我们建议将自定义元数据附加到您的 OpenRouter 请求。此元数据作为跨度属性流向 Grafana Cloud，从而可以轻松地按您自己的应用程序上下文过滤和分组跟踪：</p><p></p><pre><code>{
“型号”：“openai/gpt-4o”，
"messages": [{ "role": "user", "content": "总结本文档..." }],
“用户”：“user_12345”，
"session_id": "session_abc",
“踪迹”：{
"trace_name": "文档摘要",
“环境”：“生产”，
“特点”：“总结”
}
}
</code></pre><p>然后，您可以在 TraceQL 中查询这些属性：</p><p></p><pre><code>{ resource.service.name = "openrouter" && span.trace.metadata.feature = "summarization" }</code></pre><h3>隐私控制</h3><p>对于处理敏感数据的团队，Broadcast 支持<u><a href="https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/features/broadcast/overview#privacy-mode">隐私模式</a></u>，从跟踪中排除提示和完成内容，同时仍然发送所有操作数据，例如令牌使用情况、成本、时间和模型信息。这使您可以在不暴露 LLM 交互内容的情况下获得完整的可观察性。</p><h2>下一步</h2><p>我们将继续投资，使 LLM 可观察性尽可能无缝。我们定期添加新的集成，并致力于处理更丰富的跟踪数据，包括更精细的时序细分和质量信号，可帮助您构建更全面的可观测性仪表板。</p><p>如果您使用法学硕士进行构建并希望了解 AI 工作负载的执行情况，请为 <u><a href="https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/features/broadcast/grafana">OpenRouter 和 Grafana Cloud 集成</a></u>提供一个尝试一下。您可以在几分钟内开始使用<u><a href="https://grafana.com/auth/sign-up/create-user">免费 Grafana Cloud 帐户</a></u>和<u><a href="https://openrouter.ai">OpenRouter</a></u>帐户。</p><p><em>要了解有关 OpenRouter 广播功能和所有支持的目的地的更多信息，请访问 </em><u><em><a href="https://openrouter.ai/docs/guides/features/broadcast">广播文档</a></em></u><em>。如有疑问或反馈，请通过以下方式联系我们：</em><u><em><a href="http://openrouter.ai">openrouter.ai</a></em></u><em>。</em></p><p></p>
